The dataset contains features, such as the number of children an applicant has, where the number of unique values are relatively high, but the percentage of the total makeup is almost imperceptable. The distributions of these high cardinality variables are heavily skewed. To address this issue, the number of numeric categories was reduced to get a more accurate interpretation of their impact on the target variable.

1.2 Sampling strategies¶

Resampling the Training Data

Initially, the models were trained against training data that contained mostly non-defaulting instances. However, the model's performance on this initial training data was inferior, generally failing to classify any defaulting instances. The remedy to this issue was to resample the training data to balance the number of non-defaulting and defaulting instances. All the defaulting instances were retained, but the non-defaulting instances were randomly downsampled to match the number of non-defaulting instances. Resampled training data improved the performance of the models substantially when validated on the test data.

The test data was not resampled.

Additionally, the categroical variables were label encoded, rather than one-hot encoded.

1.2.2 Downsampling to achieve balance¶

Our metric of choice is recall, which can be improved most effectively by balancing the training set. We have used two strategies that selectively under-sample the data, but an imbalance between the number of defaulted loans and non-defaulted loans still persists. We will create a final training set that has defaults and non-defaulted loans represented equally.

def downsampling_strategy(X, y):
    y.columns = ['TARGET']
    X = X.copy(deep=True)
    y = y.copy(deep=True)
    y = y.to_frame(name = 'TARGET')
    random_state = 1
    # balancing the training set
    df = pd.concat([X, y], axis =1)
    defaults = df[df['TARGET'] == 1]
    nominal = df[df['TARGET'] == 0].sample(
        n = np.round(0.5 * (defaults.TARGET.size / 0.5)).astype(int), random_state = random_state)
    # join dataframes and shuffle
    df = pd.concat([defaults, nominal]).sample(frac = 1, random_state = random_state)
    return df
data_final = downsampling_strategy(X_tl, y_tl)

To capture at least 80% of the variability in the dataset, we must include around 150 principal components. While this is a large number of features, our previous dataset contained 302 features. Our efforts to reduce the cardinality of several features were effective.

We will pair the eigenvectors with their corresponding eigenvalues and project them onto a 2-dimensional subspace and observe the results.

1.1.2 Feature Importance Assessment¶

An analysis of feature importance was performed by removing features with high variance inflation factor (VIF) and ranking features by absolute mean feature importance from an ensemble of models (regularized logistic regression).

1.1.2.1 Feature Removal By VIF¶

High VIF is an indication of multicollinearity. Typically, limiting VIF of individual features to 5 is considered reasonable. For removal by VIF, features with high VIF were removed iteratively until the VIF for all remain features was less than 5. The VIF reduction method removed 75 features, leaving 251 features. The full list of dropped features is shown below.

1.1.2.2 Feature Importance From Ensemble¶

The training data was split into training and validation sets (80/20) split - the validation split is used in the performance estimation. Feature Importance was estimated by training a logstic model with L2 regularization and a logistic model with L1 regularization on the training set with the reduced number of features. Once the models were fit, the model weights were extracted and combined for each feature. The features were ranked by the average of the absolute value of the model weights. The table is shown below

Column Meanings

  • Mean_Abs_Weight: The mean of the absolute values of the weights assigned to features by the logistic models.
  • Feature: The feature name.
  • l1_Weight: The parameter weight assigned my the logistic model with L1 regularization.
  • l2_Weight: The parameter weight assigned my the logistic model with L2 regularization.
  • Importance_Difference: The difference btween the weight assigned by the LASSO logistic model and the weight assigned by the ridge logistic regression model.
  • Importance_Difference_%: The percent difference between the weight assigned by the LASSO logistic model and the weight assigned by the ridge logistic regression model.

1.1.2.3 Estimation of Performance Over Feature Space¶

Once the features were ranked, the number of features needed for classification was estimated by iterative training and testing a logistic model and a hist gradient boosting model on the ranked feature set. On each iteration, 5 features were added to the feature space used by the model for training and testing until the maximum feature space was reached. The following plots show the model performance over the feature space. The logistic model appears to stabilize once the top 50 features were added to the model, while the HGBM appears to stablity once the top 75 features were added to the model. The models were tested on the 20% validation split from the training data.

2. Stage Four - Modeling and Evaluation (Q2) ¶

2.1 Choose and explain your evaluation metrics (Q2A) ¶

Due to the significant overlap between the classes in our dataset, we have elected to evaluate our models using the recall metric. Recall is the ratio of accurately predicted defaults to total defaults, which allows us to extract value from the model.

2.2 Choose the method you will use for dividing your data (Q2B) ¶

We are using an 80/20 training : test set split.

As previously mentioned in section 1.2 (Data Description) we concluded that it was necessary to implement a sampling strategy on the training set in order to make a useful model for predicting loan defaults.

As a justification of the use of a generic sampling strategy with this dataset, we will provide an example of the effectiveness of simple Randum Under Sampling.

2.3 Three Classification Models (Q2C) ¶

Histogram based gradient boosting, random forest, and logistic regression were chosen for predicting loan defaults (the classification task). Each model was grid searched over values of the hyperparameters. The best results of the grid search were used in validating the model. This section shows the results of appling these models to the dataset.

2.3.1.2 Logistic Regression¶

Logistic regression is a classification model that performs well using linearly separable classes. In this case, our response classes – which refer to loan default status – are binary with a loan default represented with the integer 1 and non-default represented as integer 0. The logistic regression model utilizes an odds ratio, which represents the probability of an event occurring rather than an event not occurring. In the case of this classification model, the event – also called a “positive event” – is a representation of a loan being defaulted. The produced odds ratio is then transformed logarithmically into a probability ranging from 0 to 1. Because there is a binary split in the classification of our output, the threshold for determining if a positive event has occurred or not is 0.5.

Tuning Logstic Regression¶

Performing grid search with cross validation on the training data for tuning yielded better results. Because the results were improved, we used the regularization parameter C = 0.03. We chose this value over the top suggestion, 206.91, because the performance is relatively flat beyond the 0.03 threshold, we assessed a reasonable risk of under-regularizing.

The results of the model using hyperparameter C = 206.91 yielded 69.75% precision and 70.55% recall with accuracy recorded at 69.98%. The results of the model using hyperparameter C = 0.03 were within the same range, but agreed as slightly more reliable. At C = 0.03, precision measured at 69.90% while recall measured 70.47% with a 70.06% accuracy.

Significant Findings

As indicated in the residual plot above, there is a trend in the plotting of residuals against predicted values such that as the predicted value increases, the residuals decrease. However, the residuals increase beyond zero. Rather than forming a random spread centered roughly around zero, this trend indicates the bounding in the target variable. Further analysis and resolving issues with data sampling from the loan application process could provide a more desired random spread of actual vs. predicted values.

EXT_SOURCE_2 is standardized and bounded between the values 0 and 1. The method of standardization is not revealed; it is possible that it could be centered or transformed. However, the methodology is not revealed. Consequently, we were unable to accurately back-transform the data to determine its true distribution. Also, the bounding of the predictor variable is evident in the bounded residual pattern in the plots of residuals vs. predicted values. Despite the obvious bounding of the residuals, the residuals are randomly distributed within the boundaries of EXT_SOURCE_2.

With respect to the external cross validation statistics, the five folds in the cross validation provide the lowest mean score. However, this is not a reliable metric as the second fold's score is -111 compared to the other four that are roughly 0.15. The cause is likely due to variation in the data that is not well-managed by the linear model. To account for this issue, we used the median CV score to evaluate the fittedness of the model to the data.

2.4 Analyze the results using your chosen method of evaluation (Q2D) ¶

2.4.1 Analyze the results using your chosen method of classification evaluation (Q2D) ¶

Logistic Regression¶

With respect to the classification models, the logistic regression model was determined to be the most reliable model. In terms of classifications, the logistic regression model provided the highest precision - which will apply more caution to loan grants, thus minimizing the default rate compared to the gradient boosting and random forest models - but the lowest recall - which also indicates that the loan granting process will be less advantageous for groups at higher risk of default. Additionally, the results respective of training data were almost identical to the results of the testing data during analysis of the area under the receiver-operator curve compared to the other classification models applied. This consistency is a strong reason the logistic regression model was selected.

Moreover, trainig times for the logistic model were the lowest; close to the gradient boosting classifier (but less time nonetheless) and much less than the random forest. Respective of prediction times, the logistic model required roughly one-tenth of the time the gradient boosting and random forest models required.

2.4.2 Analyze the results using your chosen method of regression evaluation (Q2D) ¶

Bayesian Ridge Regression¶

As mentioned in the corresponding sections above, the Bayesian Ridge Regression model provided the most consistent cross-validation statistics across all folds. When considering these scores and the issues translated from the residuals plots, the Bayesian Ridge Regression model is the model selected for predicting EXT_SOURCE_2. The consistent cross validation scores are around 0.15 across all folds of the test. This indicates a more stable and reliable model than provided by pure linear regression. Additionally, Random Forest Regression did not generate useful predictions; it appears to have predicted the mean. Consequently, of the three models, Bayesian Ridge Regression is the model we selected for predicting EXT_SOURCE_2.

2.5 Discuss the advantages of each model for each classification task (Q2E) ¶

The classification results show little difference in performance between the three models (summarized in the bar chart below). However, from the ROC curves of each model, it is apparent that the tree based models (RF and HGMB) are tending to overfit to the training data dispite using hyper parameters to limit the models. If the tree based models are overfitting to the training data, then the tree based models may not perform as well as expected on new instances of data. The ROC curves for the logistic model show that it performs similarly on the training and testing set. This is an advatange of the logistic model over the tree based models.

The last pair of bar charts show the training time and prediction time for each model. The logistic model takes the least time in both cases. If this model was deployed in an environment where online retraining was necessary, the low training times of the logistic model and the HGBM model would would be a significant advantage over the random forest model. For prediction times, the logistic model is signifiantly faster. If this system was deployed in an environment where a large number of predictions were necessary, this model would provide a significant advantage over the tree based models.

The tree based models do not provide any advantages over the logistic model.

Since the model recalls are similar, the logistic regression model does not show an indication of overfitting, and the execution times of the logistic model are smaller than the other two models, we will choose this the logistic regression model for the classification task.

2.6 Which attributes from your analysis are most important (Q2F) ¶

The most important features of were revealed through a comparison of L1 and L2 regularization. The mean absolute weight of the L1 and L2 weightings was the determining factor in the selection of features for the final model.

Noteable findings:

  • Home Credit is highly dependent on third party data to predict loan defaults. Among the top ten features that determine loan defaults are three features of unknown origin, EXT_SOURCE_2, EXT_SOURCE_2, and EXT_SOURCE_3. From the given descriptions, all we know is that these features are taken from external sources, are independent of one another, and that they are standardized. It is essential that Home Credit maintain these valuable sources of data.

  • Education carries a very high significance to the model and must not be left missing. Due to its high rank, we would recommend that loan applications must continue to collect the education related data of all applicants.

  • The number of installments left in the payment plan is a positive indicator of loan default. This indicates that the risk of loan default is greatest at the beginning of the term of the loan and decreases with time.

  • As the installment payment amount rises, so does the risk of loan default. Higher payments carry more risk of loan default than do lower payments.

  • Gender disparities in loan defaults are highly significant. We recommend that collecting data based on gender, while controversial in nature, should be mandatory where permitted by law.

  • If a client produces Document 3, they are much less likely to default on a loan. We would recommend an in depth review of loan applications that are submitted without this document.

  • Car ownership strongly correlates with the risk of loan default and we would strongly reccomend the continued collection of data involving car owndership.

3. Stage Five - Deployment (Q3) ¶

3.1 Next Stage Deployment ¶

The next stage in the CRISP-DM is deployment. After model building and evaluation, we are ready to deploy our code representation of the model into a production environment and solve our original business problem. Our business problem is to give Home Credit loan evaluators access to a model that evaluates an applicant’s current and past financial history in determining whether to approve the requested loan.

How useful is your model for interested parties?¶

We believe this model would be useful for loan departments loan evaluators. This is contingent of discovering how some of the external variables are created. With this and some additional consistancy in top scoring features we could improve the accuracy

How would you measure the model's value if it was used by these parties?¶

This model should be tested in parrellel to present evaluation proceess. Then after a set period of time compare human evaluation to model based accuracy. If the results were the same, the minimum resulting savings would be the salaries of the loan evaluators. Added value would result from the acceleration of the loan approval process.

How would your deploy your model for interested parties?¶

Depending on the resources, available, models can be deployed as batch or real-time predictions. Home Credits current process is a batch implementation. The applicant fills out the form which is then digitized and sent to the loan approval department. During the loan approval, the collected data will need to be cleaned and normalized before processed through the machine learning predictive model.

How often would the model need to be updated?¶

The metrics for the customer is continually updated. On a scheduled cycle, this new dataset is analyzed through the current model. Doing batch cycles will allow for consistency in whether an applicant is approved or not. However, model designs will change as newer technology are available or changing business environments make reengineering required.

What other data should be collected?¶

In addition to the clarification of data we have described above, there would be a tremendous value in the financials for the industry that the individual is working. These financials could assist in prediction of any future concerns for the applicants present income.

# get scores from cv object
